  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and initiatives aim to create a global standard for preventing the illicit flow of funds derived from criminal activities. Key international efforts include:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Known as the Vienna Convention, it was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Known as the Palermo Convention, it requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to combat it.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats.\n   - **FATF Recommendations**: These are a comprehensive set of measures that countries are encouraged to implement, including criminalizing money laundering, establishing financial intelligence units (FIUs), and enforcing customer due diligence (CDD) requirements.\n   - **Mutual Evaluations**: FATF assesses countries' compliance with its standards and issues reports on their anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks.\n\n### 3. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These institutions work with countries to strengthen their AML frameworks through technical assistance and financial sector assessments.\n\n### 4. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) that member states must implement into their national laws. The latest, **AMLD6**, strengthens AML measures, including enhanced due diligence and transparency of beneficial ownership.\n\n### 5. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, including the **Basel AML Principles**.\n\n### 6. **Egmont Group**\n   - This is a global network of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) that facilitates international cooperation in combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### 7. **Regional Initiatives**\n   - Various regional bodies, such as the **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)** and the **Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF)**, also promote AML efforts within their regions.\n\n### Key Principles of International AML Laws\n   - Criminalization of money laundering.\n   - Reporting of suspicious transactions.\n   - Identification and verification of customers (KYC/CDD).\n   - Monitoring and record-keeping of financial transactions.\n   - Freezing and confiscation of illicit assets.\n   - International cooperation and information sharing.\n\nWhile these laws and frameworks provide a global standard, enforcement varies by country depending on national legislation and regulatory capacity. Compliance with international AML standards is essential for countries to avoid being blacklisted or facing financial sanctions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
